import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import sqlite3
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
pd.set_option('mode.chained_assignment', None)

con = sqlite3.connect('laliga.sqlite') 
sql_query = pd.read_sql("SELECT * FROM Matches", con)

df = pd.DataFrame(sql_query, columns = ['season', 'division', 'matchday','date','time', 'home_team', 'away_team', 'score'])
con.close()

df["goals_home"] = df["score"].str.split(":").str[0].astype(float)
df["goals_away"] = df["score"].str.split(":").str[1].astype(float)

conditions = [
    df['goals_home'] > df['goals_away'],
    df['goals_home'] < df['goals_away'],
    df['goals_home'] == df['goals_away']]
choices = ['Home', 'Away', 'Tie']

df['Winner'] = np.select(conditions, choices, default = 'unknown')
df = df[df['Winner']!='unknown']

winners_home_count = df['Winner'].value_counts()

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
ax = winners_home_count.plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%')
ax.set_title("Distribution of Victories 1929-2021")
plt.show()

#background function, constant intensity
def background_constant(cell_value):

    default = ''
    if cell_value == '-': return default
    
    home = int(cell_value.split(":")[0])
    away = int(cell_value.split(":")[1])
    
    score = home-away
    
    win = 'background-color: lightgreen; '
    lose = 'background-color: salmon;' 
    tie = 'background-color: yellow;' 

    if score > 0: return win
    if score < 0: return lose
    if score == 0: return tie
    return default

cross.style.applymap(background_constant)

def background_modulat(cell_value):

    default = ''
    if cell_value == '-': return default
    
    home = int(cell_value.split(":")[0])
    away = int(cell_value.split(":")[1])
    
    score = home-away
    
    opacity = abs(score)*0.2
    
    win = 'background-color: lightgreen; opacity: ' + str(opacity)
    lose = 'background-color: salmon; opacity:' + str(opacity)
    tie = 'background-color: yellow; opacity: 0.3' 

    if score > 0: return win
    if score < 0: return lose
    if score == 0: return tie
    return default

cross.style.applymap(background_modulat)

4b. Write a function that, given the season and division, plots the cross results table. Function prototype should be like plot_cross_results_table(season, division) and return the plot object.¶

In [40]:
def plot_cross_results_table(season, division):
    #from IPython.display import display
    df_s = df[df['season'] == season]
    df_s = df_s[df_s['division'] == division]
    
    cross = pd.crosstab(df_s.home_team, columns = df_s.away_team, values = df_s.score, aggfunc = 'first').fillna('-')
    
    def background(cell_value):

        default = ''
        if cell_value == '-': return default

        home = int(cell_value.split(":")[0])
        away = int(cell_value.split(":")[1])

        score = home-away

        opacity = abs(score)*0.2

        win = 'background-color: lightgreen; opacity: ' + str(opacity)
        lose = 'background-color: salmon; opacity:' + str(opacity)
        tie = 'background-color: yellow; opacity: 0.3' 

        if score > 0: return win
        if score < 0: return lose
        if score == 0: return tie
        return default
    cross = cross.style.applymap(background)
    return cross

def plot_direct_confrontations_stats(team1, team2):
    df_duel = df[(df['home_team']==team1) | (df['away_team']==team1)]
    df_duel = df_duel[(df_duel['home_team']==team2) | (df_duel['away_team']==team2)]
    df_duel['partits'] = 1

    Rivals= df_duel.groupby(['home_team']).sum()
    team1_goals  = df_duel.groupby(['home_team'])['goals_home'].sum()[0] + df_duel.groupby(['home_team'])['goals_away'].sum()[1]
    team2_goals  = df_duel.groupby(['home_team'])['goals_home'].sum()[1] + df_duel.groupby(['home_team'])['goals_away'].sum()[0]
    team1 = Rivals.index.values.tolist()[0]
    team2 = Rivals.index.values.tolist()[1]
    Rivals['total_home_goals'] = [team1_goals, team2_goals]


    plt.figure(figsize = (5,5))
    ax = Rivals['total_home_goals'].plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%',ylabel='')
    ax.set_title("Distribution of goals") 
    plt.show()

    team1_wins =  df_duel.groupby(['Winner', 'home_team'])['partits'].count()[1] + df_duel.groupby(['Winner', 'home_team'])['partits'].count()[2] 
    team2_wins =  df_duel.groupby(['Winner', 'home_team'])['partits'].count()[0] + df_duel.groupby(['Winner', 'home_team'])['partits'].count()[3] 
    ties = df_duel.groupby(['Winner', 'home_team'])['partits'].count()[4] + df_duel.groupby(['Winner', 'home_team'])['partits'].count()[5]

    plt.figure(figsize = (5,5))
    plt.pie([team1_wins, team2_wins, ties], labels = [team1, team2, 'Ties'], autopct='%1.1f%%')
    plt.title("Distribution of victories")
    plt.show()

6. Between 1979 and 1980, Real Sociedad managed to chain a total of 38 games without losing. That was, by far, the longest undefeated streak in their history. Which teams have had the longest undefeated streaks? Show the longest undefeated streaks in a horizontal bar plot, indicating in each bar the team name and the dates it held that streak, for instance, Real Sociedad 22/04/1979 - 04/05/1980.¶

In [44]:
Teams = df.groupby('home_team').sum()
teams = Teams.index.values.tolist()
df_streak = pd.DataFrame()

for team in teams:
    df_team = pd.DataFrame()
    df_streak_team = pd.DataFrame()
    df_team = df[(df['home_team']==team) | (df['away_team']==team)]
    conditions = [
        ((df_team['Winner'] == 'Home') & (df_team['home_team']==team)) |
        ((df_team['Winner'] == 'Away') & (df_team['away_team']==team)) | 
        (df_team['Winner'] == 'Tie')]
    choices = ['Yes']
    df_team = df_team.sort_values(by = 'data')

    df_team['team_wins'] = np.select(conditions, choices, default = 'No')
    df_team['start_of_streak'] = df_team.team_wins.ne(df_team['team_wins'].shift())
    df_team['streak_id'] = df_team['start_of_streak'].cumsum()
    df_team['streak_counter'] = df_team.groupby('streak_id').cumcount() + 1
    
    df_team = df_team.drop(df_team[df_team.team_wins == 'No'].index)
    
    df_streak_team['data'] = df_team['data']
    df_streak_team['streak_counter'] = df_team['streak_counter']
    df_streak_team['streak_team'] = team
    
    df_streak = df_streak.append(df_streak_team,ignore_index=True)
    
df_streak['start_of_streak'] = df_streak['streak_counter'] == 1
df_streak['end_of_streak'] = df_streak['start_of_streak'].shift(-1, fill_value=True)
df_streak.loc[df_streak['start_of_streak'], 'start_game'] = df_streak['data']
df_streak['start_game'] = df_streak['start_game'].fillna(method="ffill")
df_streak = df_streak[df_streak['end_of_streak']]
df_streak = df_streak.rename({"data": "end_game","streak_counter": "streak_length",}, axis=1)

7. Create a table with the final standings of each season (and division), that is, a table that contains all the teams ordered (in descending order) by the number of points they got during that season, and some other aggregate statistics.¶

In [47]:
final_standings = pd.DataFrame(columns=['season', 'division', 'rank', 'team', 'GF', 'GA', 'GD', 'W', 'L', 'T', 'Pts'])
grouped_games = df.groupby(['season', 'division'])
for name, group in grouped_games:
    season, division = name
    teams = group['home_team'].unique()
    for team in teams:
        home_matches = group[group['home_team'] == team]
        away_matches = group[group['away_team'] == team]
        GF = home_matches['goals_home'].sum() + away_matches['goals_away'].sum()
        GA = home_matches['goals_away'].sum() + away_matches['goals_home'].sum()
        GD = GF - GA
        W = (home_matches['Winner'] == 'Home').sum() + (away_matches['Winner'] == 'Away').sum()
        L = (home_matches['Winner'] == 'Away').sum() + (away_matches['Winner'] == 'Home').sum()
        T = (home_matches['Winner'] == 'Tie').sum() + (away_matches['Winner'] == 'Tie').sum()
        Pts = 3*W+T
        heather = pd.DataFrame({'season': season, 'division': division, 'team': team, 'GF': GF, 'GA': GA, 'GD': GD, 'W': W, 'L': L, 'T': T, 'Pts': Pts}, index=[0])
        final_standings = pd.concat([final_standings, heather], ignore_index=True)
        final_standings = final_standings.sort_values(by=['season','division','Pts', 'GD', 'GF'], ascending=[False, True, False,False,False])
        final_standings['rank'] = final_standings.groupby(['season','division'])['Pts'].rank(method='first',ascending=False)
        final_standings['rank'] = final_standings['rank'].astype(int)
final_standings

8b. Write a function that, given n team names, plots the graph described above of each one of them superposed. Function prototype should be like plot_ranking_evolution(team1, team2, ..., teamN) and return the plot object (note that function should not take one array-type argument, but n arguments). Use it to compare the evolution of all the teams that currently play in 1st division.¶

In [51]:
final_standings['first_season'] = final_standings.groupby('team')['season'].transform('min')
final_standings = final_standings.sort_values(by=['first_season', 'team'])

def plot_ranking_evolution(*teams):
    teams_df = final_standings[final_standings['team'].isin(teams)].copy()
    teams_df["first_season"] = teams_df.groupby("team")["season"].transform(min)
    teams_df = teams_df.sort_values(by=["first_season"])
    teams = teams_df["team"].unique()
    plt.figure(figsize=[20,7])  
    for team in teams:
        team_standings = final_standings[final_standings['team'] == team].copy()
        grouped_standings = team_standings.groupby(['season', 'division'])
        for name, group in grouped_standings:
            season, division = name
            N = final_standings[(final_standings['season'] == season) & (final_standings['division'] == 1)]['team'].nunique()
            if division == 1:
                team_standings.loc[group.index, 'ranked'] = group.loc[:, 'rank'] 
            elif division == 2:
                team_standings.loc[group.index, 'ranked'] = group.loc[:, 'rank'] + N
            team_standings = team_standings.sort_values(by=['season'], ascending=True)  
        plt.plot(team_standings['season'], team_standings['ranked'], label=team)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
    plt.show()
